<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-131-642  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 131 642.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  March 1989 v29 n3 p7(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A perspective on teacher technology training.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Glenn, Allen D.; Carrier, Carol A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Students in 1989 have more access to technology than students haveever had before, with approximately 1.7 million computers inpublic schools and about 90 percent of all schools having videocassette recorders.andP;  Teachers have more opportunities to learn howto use technology, but much remains to be done.andP;  The majority ofpublic school teachers have little or no technical training and donot use the computer or other advanced technologies in theirclassrooms.andP;  New teachers must receive preservice training in howto use technology, with more emphasis on using the technology inthe classroom, while active teachers must receive in-servicetraining, with more of an emphasis placed on integrating thetechnology into the curriculum.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Teacher EducationTeachingIn-Service TrainingTechnologyComputer EducationEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>